  <main>
    <section id="intro">
      <h2>Introduction</h2>
      <p>This project is prepared as part of Class 10 Computer Applications subject. It shows how pseudo-classes, pseudo-elements and advanced selectors are used in CSS with simple examples.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="pseudo">
      <h2>Pseudo-classes</h2>
      <p>Pseudo-classes are used to define the special state of an element like when the user hovers or clicks it.</p>
      <a href="#" class="btn">Hover or Click me</a>
      <pre><code>.btn:hover{ background:#2563eb; }
.btn:active{ background:#1e40af; }
</code></pre>
    </section>

    <section id="pseudoel">
      <h2 class="special-heading">Pseudo-elements</h2>
      <p>Pseudo-elements let us style specific parts of an element, such as the first letter or insert content before/after.</p>
      <pre><code>p::first-letter{ font-size:1.5em; color:blue; }
.special-heading::before{ content:"★"; }
</code></pre>
    </section>

    <section id="advanced">
      <h2>Advanced Selectors</h2>
      <p>Selectors help us target specific HTML elements. Examples include nth-child and sibling selectors.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Item 1</li>
        <li>Item 2</li>
        <li>Item 3</li>
        <li>Item 4</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="faq">
        <div class="question" tabindex="0">Click me to see answer</div>
        <div class="answer">This is the hidden answer shown using sibling selector.</div>
      </div>

      <pre><code>ul li:nth-child(odd){ background:#f3f4f6; }
.question + .answer{ display:none; }
.question.open + .answer{ display:block; }
</code></pre>
    </section>
  </main>

  <script>
    document.querySelectorAll('.faq .question').forEach(q=>{
      q.addEventListener('click', ()=> q.classList.toggle('open'));
    });
  </script>
